Over the Thanksgiving break, I heard a lot of concern about the proposed 23-story tower in Pacific Beach. The developer found a parcel technically not covered by the coastal height limit and aggregated a number of density incentives from state law to add up to a very tall project.

I support building more housing in our existing neighborhoods. I’m a founding member of San Diego YIMBY (Yes in My Backyard) Democrats and the bipartisan YIMBY Caucus in Congress. Homelessness is high where rents are high, and rents are high where supply fails to meet demand. The cost of housing is the biggest impediment to the prosperity of the Golden State, and unless we lower costs, our teachers, police, firefighters, and our children won’t be able to live here. To lower costs, we need more homes.

Part of the solution is to build more housing on underused properties in our existing neighborhoods, including coastal neighborhoods like Pacific Beach. New housing can improve neighborhoods and make them more vibrant, walkable, and safe. It’s what I did as a City Councilmember when we added 138 units on La Jolla Boulevard as part of the redesign. The Seahaus project replaced a dilapidated motel with an attractive housing project now inhabited by customers of local businesses, children in local schools, and engaged neighbors. The developer also funded the construction of two of the five roundabouts. It wasn’t easy – some neighbors even filed a petition for my recall from office. But in the end, we got more housing and a better neighborhood.

That’s not what we will get from the Pacific Beach proposal. Other home builders I’ve spoken to worry that it will taint the reputation of all development and be a poster child for those who resist all new housing. I hope the Turquoise Street developer will reconsider the proposal and offer something in better keeping with the scale of the neighborhood. I also understand that this project will likely exceed the surrounding height limit. We can accommodate taller buildings on the major streets that can still fit in. A four or six or maybe even an eight-story building on that property could provide a good number of units, still enhance the neighborhood, and provide a path for future developments of the sort. But this project, in its 23-story form, is a mistake.
